    {
        "content": "<p>Has there been any work done on Dirichlet inverses? I know that <code>number_theory.arithmetic_function</code> contains Dirichlet convolutions, but I don't think it contains Dirichlet inverses. I'm currently trying to prove that all arithmetic functions <code>f</code> whose codomain is a field and <code>f 1 ≠ 0</code> have a Dirichlet inverse.</p>",
        "id": 319457646,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1672860426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Quite a while ago me and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"387244\">@Yaël Dillies</span> wrote some stuff about incidence algebras <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/11656\">#11656</a>. We never quite wrote the inversion for arbitrary functions but it should be quite similar to the construction of mu there (its one of the TODOs). We should definitely finish and update this branch, and connect it to the arithmetic functions stuff before mathlib 4 imo!</p>",
        "id": 319464597,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1672863029
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Fully agreed, but currently no time <span aria-label=\"grinning face with smiling eyes\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f601\" role=\"img\" title=\"grinning face with smiling eyes\">:grinning_face_with_smiling_eyes:</span></p>",
        "id": 319464684,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1672863059
